# WooCommerce Product Customizer ecosystem

## Repository layout

Repositories are sibling folders under `app/src/`:

- **Main plugin**: `woocommerce-product-customizer/`
- **Add-ons** (separate packages; coordinate with the main plugin's hooks, filters, REST, and persisted data shapes):
  - `advanced-description/`
  - `conditional-logic/`
  - `extra-price/`
  - `form-builder/`
  - `multiple-choice/`
  - `stock-management/`
  - `save-your-design/`
  - `text-overlay/`

When touching shared behavior (hooks, filters, REST, data shapes), assume add-ons may depend on stable contracts from the main plugin.

## Naming and code style

- **Functions and variables**: use `snake_case` (PHP, JavaScript, and elsewhere unless the file already follows an unavoidable external API).
- **Prefixes — `mkl_pc_` for globals only**: Do **not** prefix locals, closure-scoped helpers, or names that are already scoped (PHP namespace/class, ES module, IIFE, or a host object such as `PC.*`). Use the **`mkl_pc_`** prefix only for **true globals**—functions, constants, or `window` properties intended to live in the **global PHP namespace** or on **`window`** across independently loaded scripts. Stored keys (e.g. post meta) should use a stable project prefix such as **`_mkl_pc_*`**, not `_wpc_*`.
- **Readable names — no gratuitous shortening**: prefer full words over abbreviations in project-owned identifiers (e.g. `size_label` not `size_lbl`, `options` not `opt`, `index` not `idx`, `configuration` not `cfg`). Reserve very short names only for trivial scopes where convention is universal (e.g. numeric loop counters `i` / `j`). Prefer `event` over `e` when the handler is non-trivial.
- **Formatting**: align with **WordPress coding standards** where they apply:
  - PHP: [WordPress PHP Coding Standards](https://developer.wordpress.org/coding-standards/wordpress-coding-standards/php/) (spacing, braces, Yoda conditions when required by PHPCS rulesets, escaping/sanitization, i18n).
  - JavaScript: [WordPress JS Coding Standards](https://developer.wordpress.org/coding-standards/wordpress-coding-standards/javascript/) for layout and general style, while keeping **snake_case** identifiers as the project convention.

```php
// ✅ GOOD — global PHP function (prefix at global boundary)
function mkl_pc_get_option_value( $product_id ) {
	$stored_value = get_post_meta( $product_id, '_mkl_pc_example', true );
	return $stored_value;
}
```

```php
// ✅ GOOD — class-scoped helper (no mkl_pc_ on the method; snake_case)
class Mkl_Pc_Example {
	public function format_layer_label( $raw_label ) {
		return trim( $raw_label );
	}
}
```

```javascript
// ✅ GOOD — local / module-scoped helper (no prefix; snake_case)
function format_layer_label( raw_label ) {
	const trimmed_label = raw_label.trim();
	return trimmed_label;
}
```

```javascript
// ❌ BAD — camelCase for project-owned identifiers
function formatLayerLabel( raw_label ) {
	const trimmed_label = raw_label.trim();
	return trimmed_label;
}
```

External APIs (React, WordPress globals, third-party SDKs) keep their required names; wrap or alias in snake_case at boundaries when practical.
